{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d55ba7af-33fa-448a-bbdc-b02e99004833","content":"The template is **close but not quite ready**. Here's my assessment:\n\n**✅ Present & correct:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`\n- `classifications`, `tags` (language + type)\n- `sourceName` for renaming\n- `symbols` with a valid framework choice\n\n**❌ Missing for NuGet publishing:**\n\n| Field | Why it matters |\n|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Enables validation & IntelliSense |\n| `groupIdentity` | Required for template pack versioning on NuGet |\n| `description` | Hurts discoverability without one |\n| `preferNameDirectory` | Should be `true` for project templates |\n\n**⚠️ Warning:** `net9.0` defaults as the target framework, but .NET 9 (STS) goes out of support in **May 2026** — consider making `net8.0` (LTS) the default or adding `net10.0`.\n\nYou'll also need a `.csproj` or `.nuspec` with NuGet package metadata (`PackageId`, `Version`, `Description`, `Authors`, etc.) to actually produce a publishable `.nupkg`. Want me to add the missing fields to `template.json`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3cd3c952-fe0e-49bc-94d0-d0e544fd33d4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required but strongly recommended for validation.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet template packs so multiple versions of the same template are grouped.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Works with groupIdentity for version ordering.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. The `defaultValue` is `net9.0` but we're in April 2026 — .NET 10 would be in preview. net9.0 is fine as a default though since .NET 9 is the current LTS... actually no, .NET 8 is LTS, .NET 9 is STS (released Nov 2024, support ends May 2026). \n\nSo net9.0 is about to go out of support, and net8.0 is the LTS option until November 2026, though this is a minor concern. The template structure itself is valid, and while NuGet publishing typically requires a `.nuspec` or `.csproj` with pack metadata outside of template.json, the required fields like `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, and `author` are all present in the template.json itself.\n\nLooking at what's missing, there's no `$schema` for validation, no `groupIdentity` which matters for NuGet template packs, and no `preferNameDirectory` which is standard for project templates. The `description` field is optional but recommended for discoverability on NuGet, and I should also check whether `postActions` or `sources` configurations are needed depending on the template's use case.\n\nThe main readiness issues are the missing `$schema`, `groupIdentity`, and `description` fields, plus the `net9.0` default framework which has limited support window until May 2026. I should also look for other files in the repo like a `.csproj` that might be used for NuGet packaging.","outputTokens":998,"requestId":"33C9:3FE43:1FD168A:23ACD7A:69E81BD0"},"id":"079d00aa-1635-478d-a91c-ab28d0e4d916","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:52:53.770Z","parentId":"ef2de9f5-06e0-4c6c-b3ad-d41870828d04"}
